<p>Upon reread, I'm unsure how I missed that the first time around. But although there's a lot going on under the surface, it's not a lot of worthwhile reading. The article's appeal hinges entirely on its puzzle, which requires the puzzle's solution and payoff to satisfy the reader. On the second go-around, understanding what the blue text's significance is and determining the truth of the anomaly, I find that the actual plot, Michaels' character, and the monster itself are all thoroughly underwhelming.</p>
<p>The communication method is clever, but that's it. The article needs a much more satisfying ending to be more than just a clever gimmick hiding an underwhelming twist. While I'm not a puzzle fan, my first thought is to explore ways for the DOMC and Michaels to brainstorm and execute a means of properly containing or curing the anomaly rather than just establishing that it exists in an obfuscated fashion.</p>

							</div>

								
